00:23:14.250 --> 00:23:16.527 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's Richard
Dolan talking about that.

00:23:16.527 --> 00:23:17.610 align:middle line:90%
What do you think of that?

00:23:17.610 --> 00:23:18.960 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Well, he's
absolutely right.

00:23:18.960 --> 00:23:20.085 align:middle line:90%
That's one of the problems.

00:23:20.085 --> 00:23:22.950 align:middle line:84%
For all of human history,
we've been the top dog.

00:23:22.950 --> 00:23:24.360 align:middle line:84%
We've been the
only game in town.

00:23:24.360 --> 00:23:25.110 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely.

00:23:25.110 --> 00:23:27.068 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: And now that
we're developing systems

00:23:27.068 --> 00:23:30.240 align:middle line:84%
that can compete with us or
even exceed our capacities,

00:23:30.240 --> 00:23:34.480 align:middle line:84%
we raise a lot of questions,
and we raise a lot of dangers.

00:23:34.480 --> 00:23:36.420 align:middle line:84%
It's often been stated,
even biblically,

00:23:36.420 --> 00:23:40.260 align:middle line:84%
that even a human
being has no ability

00:23:40.260 --> 00:23:41.850 align:middle line:90%
to guide his own life properly.

00:23:41.850 --> 00:23:45.660 align:middle line:84%
And if you think about it, we're
animals in a technical world

00:23:45.660 --> 00:23:48.600 align:middle line:84%
who try to develop a
sense of responsibility,

00:23:48.600 --> 00:23:51.040 align:middle line:90%
and morality, and understanding.

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:54.130 align:middle line:84%
If you have a machine that is
dispassionate, and smarter,

00:23:54.130 --> 00:23:57.070 align:middle line:84%
and more capable,
where do we stand?

00:23:57.070 --> 00:24:01.000 align:middle line:84%
We don't want to become
a part of the machine

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:03.850 align:middle line:84%
because you lose something
essential about yourself.

00:24:03.850 --> 00:24:06.580 align:middle line:84%
If you're no longer in control
of yourself, who are you?

00:24:06.580 --> 00:24:08.875 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Should we stop
doing what we're doing?

00:24:08.875 --> 00:24:10.298 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: You can't.

00:24:10.298 --> 00:24:11.590 align:middle line:90%
The genie is out of the bottle.

00:24:11.590 --> 00:24:12.400 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It is.

00:24:12.400 --> 00:24:15.010 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: It's so easy
that even people at home

00:24:15.010 --> 00:24:16.810 align:middle line:90%
are working on AI projects.

00:24:16.810 --> 00:24:19.060 align:middle line:84%
I mean, people are
creating things

00:24:19.060 --> 00:24:21.880 align:middle line:84%
unheard of before with
all the new technologies.

00:24:21.880 --> 00:24:24.910 align:middle line:84%
What we have to do
is learn how to draw

00:24:24.910 --> 00:24:28.870 align:middle line:84%
the line between how we connect
ourselves to the machinery.

00:24:28.870 --> 00:24:30.970 align:middle line:84%
Transhumanism is
wonderful and all,

00:24:30.970 --> 00:24:34.040 align:middle line:84%
and it promises a lot,
like potential immortality,

00:24:34.040 --> 00:24:36.010 align:middle line:84%
the ability to add
new limbs and senses.

00:24:36.010 --> 00:24:37.225 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: If it works well.

00:24:37.225 --> 00:24:38.350 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: If it works well.

00:24:38.350 --> 00:24:39.725 align:middle line:84%
But the problem
is it's all being

00:24:39.725 --> 00:24:42.500 align:middle line:84%
designed by human
beings who are fallible.

00:24:42.500 --> 00:24:44.900 align:middle line:84%
And if we pass the
torch to something

00:24:44.900 --> 00:24:48.590 align:middle line:84%
smarter, how do we know that
it's in our own interests?

00:24:48.590 --> 00:24:49.640 align:middle line:90%
That's one of the issues.

00:24:49.640 --> 00:24:53.157 align:middle line:84%
We must be very, very cautious,
and we must confront it.

00:24:53.157 --> 00:24:54.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Keep thinking
of the computer

00:24:54.740 --> 00:25:01.200 align:middle line:84%
Hal in "Space Odyssey," who
basically turned on his team,

00:25:01.200 --> 00:25:02.000 align:middle line:90%
didn't he?

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:02.850 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: He did.

00:25:02.850 --> 00:25:04.850 align:middle line:84%
But if you read the
next book in the series,

00:25:04.850 --> 00:25:06.980 align:middle line:84%
you discover the
reason Hal turned

00:25:06.980 --> 00:25:09.920 align:middle line:84%
was because he was
being given conflicting

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:11.360 align:middle line:90%
sets of information.

00:25:11.360 --> 00:25:14.320 align:middle line:84%
Hal himself actually seemed
to be a very moral computer

00:25:14.320 --> 00:25:16.230 align:middle line:90%
in the context of the story.

00:25:16.230 --> 00:25:19.190 align:middle line:84%
So we have to
understand, we ourselves

00:25:19.190 --> 00:25:22.340 align:middle line:84%
could be the ones that destroy
a perfectly workable system

00:25:22.340 --> 00:25:27.080 align:middle line:84%
by doing things such as lying,
deception, and improperly

00:25:27.080 --> 00:25:28.850 align:middle line:84%
formatting commands
or trying to make it

00:25:28.850 --> 00:25:30.110 align:middle line:90%
do things that conflict.

00:25:30.110 --> 00:25:32.030 align:middle line:84%
We ourselves reach
a state of confusion

00:25:32.030 --> 00:25:35.685 align:middle line:84%
when we're given conflicted
sorts of goals or orders.

00:25:35.685 --> 00:25:37.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What was
the astronaut's name?

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:38.340 align:middle line:90%
Dave?

00:25:38.340 --> 00:25:39.470 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Yes, it
was Dave Bowman.

00:25:39.470 --> 00:25:41.220 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I think it
was Dave That's right.

