00:25:50.900 --> 00:25:54.770 align:middle line:84%
And lots of things have
surrounded his career.

00:25:54.770 --> 00:25:57.140 align:middle line:90%
But what is the Fermi paradox?

00:25:57.140 --> 00:25:59.180 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: OK, so
this is the issue.

00:25:59.180 --> 00:26:01.818 align:middle line:84%
Fermi and a number
of his friends

00:26:01.818 --> 00:26:03.860 align:middle line:84%
who were working on nuclear
weaponry and research

00:26:03.860 --> 00:26:08.480 align:middle line:84%
at the time often said the
universe is ripe for life

00:26:08.480 --> 00:26:10.860 align:middle line:84%
to exist everywhere, and
there should be civilizations

00:26:10.860 --> 00:26:11.660 align:middle line:90%
everywhere.

00:26:11.660 --> 00:26:15.630 align:middle line:84%
And we don't seem to
hear any signs of them.

00:26:15.630 --> 00:26:18.122 align:middle line:84%
And so one day Fermi,
without saying anything

00:26:18.122 --> 00:26:19.580 align:middle line:84%
really technical,
just blurted out,

00:26:19.580 --> 00:26:21.080 align:middle line:90%
so where the heck are they?

00:26:21.080 --> 00:26:22.137 align:middle line:90%
And so--

00:26:22.137 --> 00:26:22.970 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: He's right.

00:26:22.970 --> 00:26:23.887 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: He is right.

00:26:23.887 --> 00:26:27.920 align:middle line:84%
The Fermi paradox got named
that because of his very simple

00:26:27.920 --> 00:26:29.300 align:middle line:90%
question, where are they?

00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:33.590 align:middle line:84%
And so I recently
taught a six-part course

00:26:33.590 --> 00:26:34.723 align:middle line:90%
on the Fermi paradox.

00:26:34.723 --> 00:26:36.140 align:middle line:84%
And this is something
interesting.

00:26:36.140 --> 00:26:38.180 align:middle line:90%
We have radio telescopes--

00:26:38.180 --> 00:26:41.150 align:middle line:84%
SETI, the Search for
Extraterrestrial Intelligence--

00:26:41.150 --> 00:26:42.680 align:middle line:90%
scanning the skies for years.

00:26:42.680 --> 00:26:44.760 align:middle line:84%
And they get some
tantalizing signals,

00:26:44.760 --> 00:26:46.760 align:middle line:84%
but they discard them
because they don't repeat.

00:26:46.760 --> 00:26:47.780 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And then it goes away.

00:26:47.780 --> 00:26:50.238 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: And, well, I mean,
if you're on a planet that has

00:26:50.238 --> 00:26:52.410 align:middle line:84%
17--hour day and we
have a 24-hour day,

00:26:52.410 --> 00:26:55.010 align:middle line:84%
and those two don't sync
up again the next day--

00:26:55.010 --> 00:26:55.550 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You'll never get it.

00:26:55.550 --> 00:26:57.450 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: You'll never get
that second signal again.

00:26:57.450 --> 00:26:59.367 align:middle line:84%
And that's one of the
easy ways of dismissing.

00:26:59.367 --> 00:27:01.325 align:middle line:84%
The other one is
they're all looking

00:27:01.325 --> 00:27:03.200 align:middle line:84%
at what they call the
water hole frequencies,

00:27:03.200 --> 00:27:04.550 align:middle line:90%
the hydroxyl frequencies.

00:27:04.550 --> 00:27:08.175 align:middle line:84%
But we have laws that
don't allow us to broadcast

00:27:08.175 --> 00:27:09.050 align:middle line:90%
on those frequencies.

00:27:09.050 --> 00:27:10.640 align:middle line:84%
Well, what if they
use the same logic?

00:27:10.640 --> 00:27:12.560 align:middle line:84%
They wouldn't be
broadcasting on them,

00:27:12.560 --> 00:27:14.930 align:middle line:84%
and the sky would
be silent there.

00:27:14.930 --> 00:27:18.440 align:middle line:84%
But nevertheless,
the issue is this--

00:27:18.440 --> 00:27:20.240 align:middle line:84%
we should have-- and
it's been estimated--

00:27:20.240 --> 00:27:23.420 align:middle line:84%
roughly three million
civilizations in this galaxy

00:27:23.420 --> 00:27:24.410 align:middle line:90%
right now.

00:27:24.410 --> 00:27:25.950 align:middle line:90%
And we don't hear from them.

00:27:25.950 --> 00:27:28.390 align:middle line:84%
So there's two
things to consider.

00:27:28.390 --> 00:27:31.420 align:middle line:84%
If they're living in the grassy
plains, or building mud huts,

00:27:31.420 --> 00:27:34.845 align:middle line:84%
or carving stone, and
don't have any electronics,

00:27:34.845 --> 00:27:37.220 align:middle line:84%
we're not going to see laser
light or hear radio signals.

00:27:37.220 --> 00:27:38.803 align:middle line:84%
They could be as
smart as-- they could

00:27:38.803 --> 00:27:40.630 align:middle line:84%
be in the Victorian
era, the steam era.

00:27:40.630 --> 00:27:43.570 align:middle line:84%
The other thing to
consider is this--

00:27:43.570 --> 00:27:46.870 align:middle line:84%
there is a natural
force in our galaxy

00:27:46.870 --> 00:27:49.630 align:middle line:84%
that could easily wipe
out civilizations.

00:27:49.630 --> 00:27:53.320 align:middle line:84%
We normally see about
50 supernovas per year

00:27:53.320 --> 00:27:55.040 align:middle line:90%
in our galaxy alone.

00:27:55.040 --> 00:27:57.280 align:middle line:84%
And a supernova has
an explosion radius.

00:27:57.280 --> 00:28:00.310 align:middle line:84%
If one was nearby us, it could
wipe out all our technology

00:28:00.310 --> 00:28:03.500 align:middle line:84%
or destroy life on Earth
depending on how close it was.

00:28:03.500 --> 00:28:05.890 align:middle line:84%
So if you take a radius
of about 50 light years

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:08.740 align:middle line:84%
as being your blast
radius of effect,

00:28:08.740 --> 00:28:10.810 align:middle line:84%
a sphere with
50-light-year radius

00:28:10.810 --> 00:28:12.700 align:middle line:90%
contains about 2,000 stars.

00:28:12.700 --> 00:28:17.710 align:middle line:84%
So when a supernova goes off,
it radiates roughly 2,000 stars.

00:28:17.710 --> 00:28:21.850 align:middle line:84%
50 supernovas means 100,000
stars in our galaxy per year

00:28:21.850 --> 00:28:23.210 align:middle line:90%
get the effects of radiation--

00:28:23.210 --> 00:28:24.460 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Which is just a blip.

00:28:24.460 --> 00:28:25.877 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: From
just a blip, right.

00:28:25.877 --> 00:28:29.330 align:middle line:84%
So in a millennium, you're
thinking, well, that's

00:28:29.330 --> 00:28:31.210 align:middle line:90%
1,000 times more than that.

00:28:31.210 --> 00:28:35.330 align:middle line:84%
You would be having a
billion stars irradiated

00:28:35.330 --> 00:28:37.550 align:middle line:90%
in 10,000 years.

00:28:37.550 --> 00:28:41.820 align:middle line:84%
Since the last ice age,
we'd have an immense number,

00:28:41.820 --> 00:28:46.740 align:middle line:84%
billions of stars being wiped
out by supernova explosions.

00:28:46.740 --> 00:28:49.680 align:middle line:84%
And all it takes
is enough radiation

00:28:49.680 --> 00:28:53.580 align:middle line:84%
to disrupt their electronics,
or turn part of their atmosphere

00:28:53.580 --> 00:28:56.398 align:middle line:84%
to ozone, or wipe out
all life on their planet.

00:28:56.398 --> 00:28:57.690 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And they're all toast.

00:28:57.690 --> 00:29:00.273 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: And they're toast, or
they're back in the Stone Age.

00:29:00.273 --> 00:29:04.110 align:middle line:84%
I mean, where would we be with
one major solar coronal mass

00:29:04.110 --> 00:29:05.130 align:middle line:90%
ejection right now?

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:06.120 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Big trouble.

00:29:06.120 --> 00:29:06.600 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Yes.

00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:08.142 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I've been
talking about that

00:29:08.142 --> 00:29:09.480 align:middle line:90%
on the radio show for years.

00:29:09.480 --> 00:29:10.522 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: That's correct.

00:29:10.522 --> 00:29:12.390 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We need to
protect our power grid,

00:29:12.390 --> 00:29:13.348 align:middle line:90%
and it's not happening.

00:29:13.348 --> 00:29:15.140 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: And you know
what the easiest way

00:29:15.140 --> 00:29:16.470 align:middle line:90%
to protect the power grid is?

00:29:16.470 --> 00:29:18.740 align:middle line:90%
Don't have one.

00:29:18.740 --> 00:29:21.320 align:middle line:84%
Everything should
be distributed.

00:29:21.320 --> 00:29:25.520 align:middle line:84%
A distributed system has
independent multiple nodes--

00:29:25.520 --> 00:29:26.788 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Instead of a domino.

00:29:26.788 --> 00:29:28.580 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: --instead of
one gigantic antenna

00:29:28.580 --> 00:29:30.170 align:middle line:84%
that's ready to get
killed in one hit.

00:29:30.170 --> 00:29:31.590 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Good point.

00:29:31.590 --> 00:29:32.390 align:middle line:90%
Good point.

00:29:32.390 --> 00:29:33.770 align:middle line:90%
What about ET life?

00:29:33.770 --> 00:29:34.700 align:middle line:90%
What's out there?

00:29:34.700 --> 00:29:36.130 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: All right.

00:29:36.130 --> 00:29:38.290 align:middle line:84%
So we know that
the stuff of life

00:29:38.290 --> 00:29:40.840 align:middle line:84%
is everywhere in the universe,
and it's called Tholen.

00:29:40.840 --> 00:29:44.740 align:middle line:84%
And it forms just from radiation
from stars, ultraviolet light,

00:29:44.740 --> 00:29:46.480 align:middle line:90%
heat, many different forces.

00:29:46.480 --> 00:29:50.540 align:middle line:84%
And we also see clouds of
these molecules in space.

00:29:50.540 --> 00:29:54.580 align:middle line:84%
So we know it's likely that
the most common life in space

00:29:54.580 --> 00:29:58.390 align:middle line:84%
would probably be bacteria--
simple, hearty organisms that

00:29:58.390 --> 00:29:59.440 align:middle line:90%
eat this stuff.

00:29:59.440 --> 00:30:00.940 align:middle line:84%
But every now and
then, you're going

00:30:00.940 --> 00:30:03.580 align:middle line:84%
to have a planet that
lives well enough, long

00:30:03.580 --> 00:30:06.490 align:middle line:84%
enough in benign
environmental conditions

00:30:06.490 --> 00:30:08.020 align:middle line:90%
that things will develop.

00:30:08.020 --> 00:30:11.290 align:middle line:84%
And we see good signs
of that sort of stuff.

00:30:11.290 --> 00:30:14.740 align:middle line:84%
Even on Mars, there appear to
be fossil remains, although they

00:30:14.740 --> 00:30:15.860 align:middle line:90%
don't talk about it.

00:30:15.860 --> 00:30:18.340 align:middle line:84%
But we do know that bacteria
should be everywhere.

00:30:18.340 --> 00:30:20.680 align:middle line:84%
And given enough time
and benign conditions,

00:30:20.680 --> 00:30:23.530 align:middle line:84%
it's quite likely that
there's every sort of organism

00:30:23.530 --> 00:30:26.080 align:middle line:84%
you can imagine living
somewhere in space.

00:30:26.080 --> 00:30:29.500 align:middle line:84%
And also consider what we
think of as life-supporting

00:30:29.500 --> 00:30:30.670 align:middle line:90%
conditions on Earth--

00:30:30.670 --> 00:30:32.800 align:middle line:90%
we're very human-centric.

00:30:32.800 --> 00:30:35.780 align:middle line:84%
We think of conditions like
this much oxygen, temperature,

00:30:35.780 --> 00:30:36.580 align:middle line:90%
pressure.

00:30:36.580 --> 00:30:39.370 align:middle line:84%
But there are conditions
that would kill us instantly

00:30:39.370 --> 00:30:42.290 align:middle line:84%
that would support a lot of
other life forms quite well.

00:30:42.290 --> 00:30:44.830 align:middle line:84%
So you can expect
billions of worlds

00:30:44.830 --> 00:30:47.020 align:middle line:84%
with life that we wouldn't
be able to step foot

00:30:47.020 --> 00:30:48.345 align:middle line:90%
on without dying.

00:30:48.345 --> 00:30:49.720 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's the
Drake equation.

00:30:49.720 --> 00:30:51.428 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Well, it is
the Drake equation.

00:30:51.428 --> 00:30:54.100 align:middle line:84%
And we have to recognize
that the parameters

00:30:54.100 --> 00:30:55.540 align:middle line:84%
for the existence
of life are much

00:30:55.540 --> 00:30:58.967 align:middle line:84%
broader than the parameters
that exist for human life.

00:30:58.967 --> 00:30:59.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely.

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:03.580 align:middle line:84%
Now, how do we determine
where these signals

00:31:03.580 --> 00:31:05.798 align:middle line:90%
are coming from out there?

00:31:05.798 --> 00:31:08.090 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Well, there are a
number of things we can do.

00:31:08.090 --> 00:31:11.740 align:middle line:84%
And one of them is you set up
a number of radio telescopes

00:31:11.740 --> 00:31:13.690 align:middle line:84%
or a number of
infrared telescopes,

00:31:13.690 --> 00:31:17.122 align:middle line:84%
and you use what's known as very
long baseline interferometry.

00:31:17.122 --> 00:31:18.580 align:middle line:84%
So the signals from
all of them are

00:31:18.580 --> 00:31:21.700 align:middle line:84%
synchronized to extract
as much data as you can.

00:31:21.700 --> 00:31:24.930 align:middle line:84%
And it effectively gives you
a lens the size of the Earth.

00:31:24.930 --> 00:31:26.940 align:middle line:84%
And with that
resolution, we should

00:31:26.940 --> 00:31:30.330 align:middle line:84%
be able to identify components
in the atmospheres of planets

00:31:30.330 --> 00:31:32.340 align:middle line:84%
that look like the
exhaust of biology,

00:31:32.340 --> 00:31:36.420 align:middle line:84%
like excess oxygen or certain
gases that might exist only

00:31:36.420 --> 00:31:39.240 align:middle line:90%
from organisms' operation.

00:31:39.240 --> 00:31:41.670 align:middle line:84%
And so we could find
signals that way.

00:31:41.670 --> 00:31:43.362 align:middle line:90%
But here's another one.

00:31:43.362 --> 00:31:45.980 align:middle line:84%
One of the things we don't
have around our planet

00:31:45.980 --> 00:31:49.075 align:middle line:84%
is orbital power stations
that harvest the sunlight,

00:31:49.075 --> 00:31:51.200 align:middle line:84%
turn it into microwaves,
and beam it to the ground.

00:31:51.200 --> 00:31:51.730 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Beams it
right down to us.

00:31:51.730 --> 00:31:53.250 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Right, orbital power.

00:31:53.250 --> 00:31:56.540 align:middle line:84%
Well, if a civilization
used orbital power,

00:31:56.540 --> 00:31:59.870 align:middle line:84%
you can expect that an
array of satellites orbiting

00:31:59.870 --> 00:32:02.570 align:middle line:84%
their planet would have
enough leakage or side

00:32:02.570 --> 00:32:04.370 align:middle line:84%
lobes that we should
be able to detect

00:32:04.370 --> 00:32:10.037 align:middle line:84%
a fairly strong synchronized
signal, even from here.

00:32:10.037 --> 00:32:10.870 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Good point.

00:32:10.870 --> 00:32:12.662 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: So some things
we could look for.

00:32:12.662 --> 00:32:14.490 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: 4,000 light
years away, there

00:32:14.490 --> 00:32:18.510 align:middle line:84%
was a strange radio
signal emanating from it.

00:32:18.510 --> 00:32:19.510 align:middle line:90%
Let's check.

00:32:19.510 --> 00:32:20.310 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:32:20.310 --> 00:32:23.550 align:middle line:10%
- Scientists have detected a
radio signal from somewhere

00:32:23.550 --> 00:32:27.660 align:middle line:10%
out in deep space some
4,000 light years away.

00:32:27.660 --> 00:32:32.010 align:middle line:84%
The signal pulsed every
18 minutes and 18 seconds

00:32:32.010 --> 00:32:33.540 align:middle line:90%
every time--

00:32:33.540 --> 00:32:36.780 align:middle line:90%
18 minutes and 18 seconds.

00:32:36.780 --> 00:32:39.390 align:middle line:90%
It did this for three months.

00:32:39.390 --> 00:32:42.090 align:middle line:90%
Then it stopped.

00:32:42.090 --> 00:32:45.660 align:middle line:84%
Scientists assume it was a
naturally occurring rotating

00:32:45.660 --> 00:32:49.470 align:middle line:84%
object that, like a
lighthouse shining its beacon,

00:32:49.470 --> 00:32:52.800 align:middle line:84%
will send what appears
to be a repeating signal.

00:32:52.800 --> 00:32:55.560 align:middle line:10%
But Natasha Hurley
Walker, whose study

00:32:55.560 --> 00:32:57.750 align:middle line:10%
into this repeating
signal was recently

00:32:57.750 --> 00:33:00.780 align:middle line:10%
published in the journal
"Nature" told Vice,

00:33:00.780 --> 00:33:04.770 align:middle line:10%
quote, "there are no models
that produce such bright radio

00:33:04.770 --> 00:33:07.920 align:middle line:10%
emission from two objects
in orbit with each other,

00:33:07.920 --> 00:33:11.220 align:middle line:10%
with such precision, and
any that would produce

00:33:11.220 --> 00:33:14.520 align:middle line:10%
any kind of radio waves
would also produce X-ray

00:33:14.520 --> 00:33:16.680 align:middle line:10%
emission, which we don't see."

00:33:16.680 --> 00:33:20.730 align:middle line:84%
Some think this might be coming
from a highly magnetized star

00:33:20.730 --> 00:33:22.380 align:middle line:90%
called a magnetar.

00:33:22.380 --> 00:33:25.970 align:middle line:10%
So what does this all mean?

00:33:25.970 --> 00:33:30.500 align:middle line:10%
Astronomer and Gaia News
contributor, Marc Dantonio.

00:33:30.500 --> 00:33:35.240 align:middle line:10%
- Maybe this strange signal
is some weird kind of magnetar

00:33:35.240 --> 00:33:36.920 align:middle line:10%
that is rotating.

00:33:36.920 --> 00:33:41.420 align:middle line:84%
And we're not used to seeing
it rotate every 18 minutes.

00:33:41.420 --> 00:33:43.710 align:middle line:84%
That means a rather
slow rotation.

00:33:43.710 --> 00:33:45.420 align:middle line:90%
So this is kind of weird.

00:33:45.420 --> 00:33:48.710 align:middle line:84%
It's something that doesn't
match any model that we know.

00:33:48.710 --> 00:33:53.390 align:middle line:10%
And I think that it takes
us down a new research path

00:33:53.390 --> 00:33:56.920 align:middle line:10%
to try and figure out just
what it is we're looking at.

00:33:56.920 --> 00:34:00.080 align:middle line:84%
- If this signal is not
from some type of dead star,

00:34:00.080 --> 00:34:02.667 align:middle line:90%
what else could it be?

00:34:02.667 --> 00:34:04.750 align:middle line:10%
- There is a remote chance--
there's a remote one,

00:34:04.750 --> 00:34:09.310 align:middle line:10%
a far remote one-- that it's
a techno signature, maybe.

00:34:09.310 --> 00:34:10.989 align:middle line:10%
Now, what's a techno signature?

00:34:10.989 --> 00:34:13.210 align:middle line:84%
It's a signature from
something intelligent

00:34:13.210 --> 00:34:14.770 align:middle line:90%
that's beeping out something.

00:34:14.770 --> 00:34:18.670 align:middle line:84%
Now, repeating bursts
like this, we always

00:34:18.670 --> 00:34:21.010 align:middle line:84%
err on the side of caution
and say, well, the universe

00:34:21.010 --> 00:34:21.639 align:middle line:90%
rotates.

00:34:21.639 --> 00:34:22.480 align:middle line:90%
Everything rotates.

00:34:22.480 --> 00:34:24.313 align:middle line:84%
So therefore, it could
be something rotating

00:34:24.313 --> 00:34:29.860 align:middle line:84%
and flashing a hot side toward
us that has this signal in it

00:34:29.860 --> 00:34:30.940 align:middle line:90%
like a hot spot.

00:34:30.940 --> 00:34:32.830 align:middle line:84%
So it could either
be something that's

00:34:32.830 --> 00:34:34.600 align:middle line:84%
a techno signature
that's intelligent,

00:34:34.600 --> 00:34:37.870 align:middle line:84%
or it could be a naturally
occurring, strange,

00:34:37.870 --> 00:34:41.060 align:middle line:84%
exotic star or magnetar,
something along those lines.

00:34:41.060 --> 00:34:41.860 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:34:41.860 --> 00:34:44.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What in the
world could it be?

00:34:44.920 --> 00:34:46.703 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: [LAUGHS]
What out of the world?

00:34:46.703 --> 00:34:47.620 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:34:47.620 --> 00:34:49.360 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Well,
there are a number

00:34:49.360 --> 00:34:51.530 align:middle line:84%
of things that could
produce a signal like that.

00:34:51.530 --> 00:34:54.820 align:middle line:84%
And it's very easy to go right
to an intelligent source.

00:34:54.820 --> 00:34:57.340 align:middle line:84%
And that's not out
of the question.

00:34:57.340 --> 00:35:00.080 align:middle line:84%
It's just so distant, and we
have so little information

00:35:00.080 --> 00:35:01.030 align:middle line:90%
it's hard to say.

00:35:01.030 --> 00:35:05.860 align:middle line:84%
But if you had a cloud of gas,
for instance, orbiting the star

00:35:05.860 --> 00:35:09.640 align:middle line:84%
and a beam of energy coming
from the star and exciting it,

00:35:09.640 --> 00:35:11.800 align:middle line:84%
obviously, it could
produce radio waves.

00:35:11.800 --> 00:35:13.610 align:middle line:84%
We've seen things
similar to that.

00:35:13.610 --> 00:35:16.540 align:middle line:84%
But the statement about
it probably also producing

00:35:16.540 --> 00:35:17.740 align:middle line:90%
X-rays--

00:35:17.740 --> 00:35:19.550 align:middle line:84%
in most cases,
that would be true.

00:35:19.550 --> 00:35:21.430 align:middle line:84%
So it could be a new
phenomenon, something

00:35:21.430 --> 00:35:22.510 align:middle line:90%
we're not familiar with.

00:35:22.510 --> 00:35:24.580 align:middle line:84%
It could be a
technical signature.

00:35:24.580 --> 00:35:26.110 align:middle line:84%
It could be something
very prosaic,

00:35:26.110 --> 00:35:27.730 align:middle line:90%
and we're missing something.

00:35:27.730 --> 00:35:30.775 align:middle line:84%
I won't discount intelligence
because, in my mind,

00:35:30.775 --> 00:35:33.025 align:middle line:84%
there has to be a lot of
intelligence in the universe.

00:35:33.025 --> 00:35:35.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: When you and I
first met on the radio,

00:35:35.050 --> 00:35:37.330 align:middle line:90%
we talked about Mars anomalies.

00:35:37.330 --> 00:35:38.920 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Yes.

00:35:38.920 --> 00:35:41.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What's your
take on Mars these days?

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:43.480 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: To me,
it's very obvious.

00:35:43.480 --> 00:35:45.880 align:middle line:84%
Earth and Mars both formed
from the same materials

00:35:45.880 --> 00:35:48.340 align:middle line:84%
in the same solar
system at the same time.

00:35:48.340 --> 00:35:50.400 align:middle line:84%
And you would expect that
many of the conditions

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:51.200 align:middle line:90%
would be the same.

00:35:51.200 --> 00:35:52.870 align:middle line:90%
They're both terrestrial worlds.

00:35:52.870 --> 00:35:55.420 align:middle line:84%
And the formation of
atmospheres, water,

00:35:55.420 --> 00:35:58.810 align:middle line:84%
petroleum-- those processes
occur in the molten

00:35:58.810 --> 00:36:02.170 align:middle line:84%
magma in the planet
and then exit

00:36:02.170 --> 00:36:03.550 align:middle line:90%
to the surface of the planet.

00:36:03.550 --> 00:36:06.262 align:middle line:84%
That's where our oceans and
petroleum all came from.

00:36:06.262 --> 00:36:08.220 align:middle line:84%
Similar processes should
have happened on Mars.

00:36:08.220 --> 00:36:09.160 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Abiotic oil.

00:36:09.160 --> 00:36:10.240 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Absolutely.

00:36:10.240 --> 00:36:13.240 align:middle line:84%
And actually, some of the
subsurface radar scans

00:36:13.240 --> 00:36:16.540 align:middle line:84%
appear to indicate
occlusions underground

00:36:16.540 --> 00:36:18.130 align:middle line:90%
that might be salt domes.

00:36:18.130 --> 00:36:21.220 align:middle line:84%
That would be very consistent
with the oceanic environment

00:36:21.220 --> 00:36:24.430 align:middle line:84%
being generated by
chemistry and magma.

00:36:24.430 --> 00:36:27.220 align:middle line:84%
We also do know the whole
North Pole of the planet

00:36:27.220 --> 00:36:29.710 align:middle line:84%
was covered in an
ocean at one time,

00:36:29.710 --> 00:36:31.330 align:middle line:84%
and there were
oceans all over Mars.

00:36:31.330 --> 00:36:33.620 align:middle line:84%
And they dried up
quite a while ago.

00:36:33.620 --> 00:36:37.510 align:middle line:84%
Most people, particularly in
higher research organizations,

00:36:37.510 --> 00:36:40.180 align:middle line:84%
say the water went away four
billion or two billion years

00:36:40.180 --> 00:36:42.100 align:middle line:84%
ago and wasn't a
chance for anything

00:36:42.100 --> 00:36:44.020 align:middle line:90%
to grow there or live there.

00:36:44.020 --> 00:36:46.360 align:middle line:84%
I think that's wrong, that
the planet is presently

00:36:46.360 --> 00:36:47.440 align:middle line:90%
in an ice age.

00:36:47.440 --> 00:36:50.470 align:middle line:84%
And we see signs of that
from the Mars Polar Lander.

00:36:50.470 --> 00:36:53.110 align:middle line:84%
It found ice only a couple
of inches under the soil.

00:36:53.110 --> 00:36:55.270 align:middle line:84%
And we often see
slope streaks forming

00:36:55.270 --> 00:36:58.180 align:middle line:84%
in craters where this ice is
apparently melting and flowing

00:36:58.180 --> 00:36:59.060 align:middle line:90%
as water.

00:36:59.060 --> 00:37:01.030 align:middle line:84%
So it's very clear
to me, Mars was

00:37:01.030 --> 00:37:04.000 align:middle line:84%
a smaller world than the Earth,
less gravity, less volcanism.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:06.220 align:middle line:84%
It couldn't regenerate
its atmosphere the way

00:37:06.220 --> 00:37:08.470 align:middle line:84%
our volcanoes on Earth
regenerate our own.

00:37:08.470 --> 00:37:11.980 align:middle line:84%
And being in an ice age
with the oceans frozen,

00:37:11.980 --> 00:37:13.630 align:middle line:90%
well, the air gets lost.

00:37:13.630 --> 00:37:14.830 align:middle line:90%
It gets very thin.

00:37:14.830 --> 00:37:17.345 align:middle line:84%
But one thing
stands in its favor.

00:37:17.345 --> 00:37:18.220 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: What's that?

00:37:18.220 --> 00:37:21.910 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Organisms can live
in water even in a near vacuum.

00:37:21.910 --> 00:37:22.810 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Absolutely.

00:37:22.810 --> 00:37:26.640 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: And so the water
acts as a surrogate atmosphere.

00:37:26.640 --> 00:37:31.180 align:middle line:84%
We were involved in some of the
research done on samples back

00:37:31.180 --> 00:37:31.980 align:middle line:90%
from the moon.

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:34.650 align:middle line:84%
And the Johnson Space
Flight Center many years ago

00:37:34.650 --> 00:37:38.040 align:middle line:84%
did research, and they took
small cold-blooded animals

00:37:38.040 --> 00:37:41.570 align:middle line:84%
and dropped them down to a
tenth of an atmosphere, 1.5

00:37:41.570 --> 00:37:44.020 align:middle line:90%
pounds of pressure.

00:37:44.020 --> 00:37:46.850 align:middle line:84%
And they survived after
adapting quite well.

00:37:46.850 --> 00:37:49.300 align:middle line:84%
So there were fish, and
reptiles, and other things

00:37:49.300 --> 00:37:51.910 align:middle line:84%
that lived in just a tenth of
the atmosphere our planet has.

00:37:51.910 --> 00:37:54.250 align:middle line:84%
They were able to
adapt and thrive.

00:37:54.250 --> 00:37:56.300 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Let's look at
some of these Mars images.

00:37:56.300 --> 00:37:57.175 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Absolutely.

00:37:57.175 --> 00:37:59.342 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tell us what we're
looking at, Sir Charles.

00:37:59.342 --> 00:38:00.610 align:middle line:90%
Here's our first one.

00:38:00.610 --> 00:38:03.175 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: OK, so what I'd
like to show you in figure 1--

00:38:03.175 --> 00:38:04.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: We'll start
up there in the corner.

00:38:04.670 --> 00:38:05.545 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Absolutely.

00:38:05.545 --> 00:38:08.320 align:middle line:84%
So figure 1 shows what
is clearly dry sand.

00:38:08.320 --> 00:38:12.740 align:middle line:84%
You can see a print made by
the Mossbauer spectrometer

00:38:12.740 --> 00:38:13.540 align:middle line:90%
on the left.

00:38:13.540 --> 00:38:16.300 align:middle line:10%
And then the next day, you
see that it has worn away.

00:38:16.300 --> 00:38:19.720 align:middle line:84%
This is day-by-day erosion
that we have a track of.

00:38:19.720 --> 00:38:20.710 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Pretty fast.

00:38:20.710 --> 00:38:21.510 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: It is.

00:38:21.510 --> 00:38:23.620 align:middle line:84%
And you see they
take numerous frames

00:38:23.620 --> 00:38:26.480 align:middle line:84%
of the same area over many
days on Mars, or SOLs,

00:38:26.480 --> 00:38:27.280 align:middle line:90%
as they're called.

00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:29.530 align:middle line:84%
And we can see the rate
that change is occurring.

00:38:29.530 --> 00:38:32.440 align:middle line:84%
In figure 2, you
see a stretch of mud

00:38:32.440 --> 00:38:35.440 align:middle line:84%
before and after the Mossbauer
head was pressed into it,

00:38:35.440 --> 00:38:37.210 align:middle line:84%
and you see that
ring-shaped print.

00:38:37.210 --> 00:38:43.400 align:middle line:10%
The closeup in figure 4
shows a trail in the mud--

00:38:43.400 --> 00:38:45.460 align:middle line:10%
and it does appear to
be mud on the left.

00:38:45.460 --> 00:38:47.710 align:middle line:10%
On the right, that
trail has altered

00:38:47.710 --> 00:38:50.560 align:middle line:10%
as if some water or some
liquid has flowed over it

00:38:50.560 --> 00:38:51.748 align:middle line:10%
in the course of the night.

00:38:51.748 --> 00:38:53.290 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now, when
you say mud, we're

00:38:53.290 --> 00:38:55.300 align:middle line:90%
talking about wet, soggy mud.

00:38:55.300 --> 00:38:56.350 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Wet, soggy mud.

00:38:56.350 --> 00:38:58.360 align:middle line:90%
So look at the ring print.

00:38:58.360 --> 00:39:00.640 align:middle line:84%
If you look at
the figure 5, I've

00:39:00.640 --> 00:39:02.950 align:middle line:84%
colorized an outline to
show that it is exactly

00:39:02.950 --> 00:39:03.880 align:middle line:90%
the same area.

00:39:03.880 --> 00:39:05.740 align:middle line:84%
The patterns in
the spherules prove

00:39:05.740 --> 00:39:08.650 align:middle line:84%
that it is the same area just
from two different photos.

00:39:08.650 --> 00:39:13.660 align:middle line:10%
In figure 6, at the bottom, you
see a dark area in the ring.

00:39:13.660 --> 00:39:15.627 align:middle line:10%
That is where the mud
stuck to the Mossbauer.

00:39:15.627 --> 00:39:16.960 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: That's enhanced, right?

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:17.305 align:middle line:10%
>>SHULTS: Yes.

00:39:17.305 --> 00:39:19.045 align:middle line:10%
>>NOORY: Figure 6 is 5 enhanced?

00:39:19.045 --> 00:39:20.020 align:middle line:10%
OK.

00:39:20.020 --> 00:39:20.820 align:middle line:10%
>>SHULTS: Yep.

00:39:20.820 --> 00:39:23.710 align:middle line:10%
So figure 6 shows you
where the mud bulges.

00:39:23.710 --> 00:39:26.500 align:middle line:10%
It doesn't flow like
sand in figure 1.

00:39:26.500 --> 00:39:30.010 align:middle line:84%
Figure 7 shows where the mud
is sticking on the instrument.

00:39:30.010 --> 00:39:31.780 align:middle line:90%
My contention is very simple.

00:39:31.780 --> 00:39:35.813 align:middle line:84%
Dry sand does not stick to
a plate of dry aluminum.

00:39:35.813 --> 00:39:36.730 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:39:36.730 --> 00:39:38.860 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: And that
print is an exact mirror

00:39:38.860 --> 00:39:41.290 align:middle line:84%
image of the mud that
peeled out of that print.

00:39:41.290 --> 00:39:45.340 align:middle line:84%
This shows water had to
flow within a 24-hour period

00:39:45.340 --> 00:39:47.690 align:middle line:84%
in order to make that
change in the mud.

00:39:47.690 --> 00:39:49.840 align:middle line:84%
And it also shows
that it must indeed

00:39:49.840 --> 00:39:51.940 align:middle line:84%
be wet because the
bulging you see

00:39:51.940 --> 00:39:55.450 align:middle line:84%
there is totally different
from the print in the sand.

00:39:55.450 --> 00:39:59.120 align:middle line:84%
Now, this is the most important
part about these images.

00:39:59.120 --> 00:40:01.790 align:middle line:84%
We know that these
features are being

00:40:01.790 --> 00:40:05.310 align:middle line:90%
eroded on a day-by-day basis.

00:40:05.310 --> 00:40:07.400 align:middle line:84%
So these features
must not be new.

00:40:07.400 --> 00:40:10.410 align:middle line:90%
They had to be created recently.

00:40:10.410 --> 00:40:12.680 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Which means
the planet is alive--

00:40:12.680 --> 00:40:13.520 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: It is wet.

00:40:13.520 --> 00:40:14.150 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: --and wet.

00:40:14.150 --> 00:40:15.192 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: That's correct.

00:40:15.192 --> 00:40:16.700 align:middle line:84%
And so there are
many, many-- there

00:40:16.700 --> 00:40:18.350 align:middle line:84%
are thousands of
images showing what

00:40:18.350 --> 00:40:21.500 align:middle line:84%
appears to be the change from
liquid water in the course

00:40:21.500 --> 00:40:23.690 align:middle line:90%
of two to five days.

00:40:23.690 --> 00:40:27.530 align:middle line:84%
And NASA does not embrace
this or even discuss

00:40:27.530 --> 00:40:30.620 align:middle line:84%
this, which is amazing
to me because the signs

00:40:30.620 --> 00:40:33.350 align:middle line:84%
of the physics and the
chemistry are very, very

00:40:33.350 --> 00:40:36.530 align:middle line:84%
consistent with one thing,
and that's liquid water.

00:40:36.530 --> 00:40:39.320 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You have spotted
fossils on Mars, haven't you?

00:40:39.320 --> 00:40:40.362 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Indeed, indeed.

00:40:40.362 --> 00:40:41.528 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's fascinating.

00:40:41.528 --> 00:40:43.100 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Well, and
here's the thing.

00:40:43.100 --> 00:40:45.260 align:middle line:84%
If you find one
anomalous thing that

00:40:45.260 --> 00:40:48.620 align:middle line:84%
looks like a shell, or an
urchin, or a trilobite,

00:40:48.620 --> 00:40:50.990 align:middle line:84%
you think, well,
maybe random erosion

00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:52.330 align:middle line:90%
produced an odd feature.

00:40:52.330 --> 00:40:54.990 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Once, which
happens, which happens.

00:40:54.990 --> 00:40:55.790 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Right.

00:40:55.790 --> 00:40:59.330 align:middle line:84%
But if you find five,
or 30, or 1,000 of them,

00:40:59.330 --> 00:41:01.527 align:middle line:84%
you know that erosion
is a random force.

00:41:01.527 --> 00:41:03.110 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Scattered
all over the place.

00:41:03.110 --> 00:41:03.910 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: Exactly.

00:41:03.910 --> 00:41:06.180 align:middle line:84%
You're literally crunching
on them under your feet.

00:41:06.180 --> 00:41:08.180 align:middle line:84%
And I had one
fellow from NASA who

00:41:08.180 --> 00:41:10.178 align:middle line:84%
objected it, says there's
no place in the world

00:41:10.178 --> 00:41:12.470 align:middle line:84%
here on Earth where there's
life that you'd walk around

00:41:12.470 --> 00:41:13.845 align:middle line:84%
and crunch on
fossils everywhere.

00:41:13.845 --> 00:41:14.750 align:middle line:90%
And I objected.

00:41:14.750 --> 00:41:17.430 align:middle line:84%
I said, no, I live in
Florida, and there's limestone

00:41:17.430 --> 00:41:18.230 align:middle line:90%
everywhere.

00:41:18.230 --> 00:41:20.300 align:middle line:84%
And everywhere you
walk, you're crunching.

00:41:20.300 --> 00:41:22.040 align:middle line:84%
And if you pick
up off the ground,

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:26.102 align:middle line:84%
you pick up a crinoid stem,
or a sea biscuit, or a shell.

00:41:26.102 --> 00:41:28.310 align:middle line:84%
it's no different on Mars
in these areas they landed.

00:41:28.310 --> 00:41:31.430 align:middle line:84%
They're all dried, saline
environments-- oceans

00:41:31.430 --> 00:41:32.300 align:middle line:90%
and lakes.

00:41:32.300 --> 00:41:35.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Let's talk about the
possibility of life on Mars.

00:41:35.480 --> 00:41:37.220 align:middle line:84%
Let's look at a
report from Gaia News.

00:41:37.220 --> 00:41:38.020 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: OK.

00:41:38.020 --> 00:41:38.820 align:middle line:90%
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:41:38.820 --> 00:41:41.150 align:middle line:84%
- The final transmission
from the Mars Pathfinder

00:41:41.150 --> 00:41:44.460 align:middle line:90%
was on September 27, 1997.

00:41:44.460 --> 00:41:47.060 align:middle line:84%
But the data it provided
helped scientists

00:41:47.060 --> 00:41:50.060 align:middle line:84%
to conclude Mars was
once wet and warm.

00:41:50.060 --> 00:41:52.400 align:middle line:10%
And rounded rocks on
the surface indicate

00:41:52.400 --> 00:41:54.770 align:middle line:10%
they may have been worn
down by running water.

00:41:54.770 --> 00:42:00.140 align:middle line:10%
And if there was water,
there could have been life.

00:42:00.140 --> 00:42:04.010 align:middle line:84%
Flash forward to today,
NASA's Perseverance Rover,

00:42:04.010 --> 00:42:07.310 align:middle line:84%
on the red planet
since February of 2021,

00:42:07.310 --> 00:42:10.220 align:middle line:84%
is tasked with finding
past or present life

00:42:10.220 --> 00:42:14.540 align:middle line:84%
and seeing if humans could one
day explore or colonize Mars.

00:42:14.540 --> 00:42:16.820 align:middle line:10%
Perseverance is
collecting samples

00:42:16.820 --> 00:42:20.930 align:middle line:10%
to determine if they contain
any fossils of ancient martians.

00:42:20.930 --> 00:42:24.770 align:middle line:84%
But a new study led by
Alexander Pavlov, a space

00:42:24.770 --> 00:42:29.330 align:middle line:84%
scientist at NASA, says they
might have to dig a lot deeper.

00:42:29.330 --> 00:42:33.140 align:middle line:84%
Pavlov argues that amino acids
could be the best evidence

00:42:33.140 --> 00:42:35.270 align:middle line:90%
of any past life on Mars.

00:42:35.270 --> 00:42:37.850 align:middle line:10%
But after millions of
years of radiation,

00:42:37.850 --> 00:42:40.040 align:middle line:10%
all those amino
acids on the surface

00:42:40.040 --> 00:42:42.780 align:middle line:10%
would have been
destroyed, writing, quote,

00:42:42.780 --> 00:42:45.860 align:middle line:10%
"Our experimental results
suggest serious challenges

00:42:45.860 --> 00:42:48.320 align:middle line:10%
for the search of
ancient amino acids

00:42:48.320 --> 00:42:52.100 align:middle line:10%
and other potential organic
biosignatures in the top 2

00:42:52.100 --> 00:42:54.170 align:middle line:10%
meters of the martian surface."

00:42:54.170 --> 00:42:58.160 align:middle line:84%
2 meters, or roughly 7
feet, but Perseverance

00:42:58.160 --> 00:43:00.480 align:middle line:90%
can only dig a few inches.

00:43:00.480 --> 00:43:04.790 align:middle line:10%
However, Pavlov told
vicenews.com, quote,

00:43:04.790 --> 00:43:07.880 align:middle line:10%
"Microcraters are
common on Mars.

00:43:07.880 --> 00:43:10.280 align:middle line:10%
Small impactors
can excavate rocks

00:43:10.280 --> 00:43:12.350 align:middle line:10%
from several meters of depth.

00:43:12.350 --> 00:43:16.070 align:middle line:10%
Cosmic rays are significantly
reduced by 2-meter depth

00:43:16.070 --> 00:43:20.370 align:middle line:10%
into a rock and do not
penetrate at all below 4 meters.

00:43:20.370 --> 00:43:23.000 align:middle line:10%
Therefore, an ejecta
from such depths

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.700 align:middle line:10%
would have small exposure
time to cosmic rays

00:43:25.700 --> 00:43:29.870 align:middle line:10%
and thus, may contain the
primordial unaltered amino

00:43:29.870 --> 00:43:32.750 align:middle line:10%
acids from billions
of years ago."

00:43:32.750 --> 00:43:36.320 align:middle line:10%
25 years of humans studying
the surface of Mars,

00:43:36.320 --> 00:43:38.570 align:middle line:10%
and we have learned so much.

00:43:38.570 --> 00:43:41.580 align:middle line:10%
But as Pavlov
concluded in his study,

00:43:41.580 --> 00:43:45.320 align:middle line:10%
we have only scratched the
surface of this problem.

00:43:45.320 --> 00:43:47.800 align:middle line:84%
But with every problem
comes the opportunity

00:43:47.800 --> 00:43:49.540 align:middle line:90%
to figure out a solution.

00:43:49.540 --> 00:43:53.200 align:middle line:84%
And perhaps this will
help us find life on Mars.

00:43:53.200 --> 00:43:54.130 align:middle line:90%
[END PLAYBACK]

00:43:54.130 --> 00:43:56.260 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What amazing
technology, Sir Charles.

00:43:56.260 --> 00:43:57.680 align:middle line:90%
What does that tell you?

00:43:57.680 --> 00:43:59.097 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Well,
it tells me a lot.

00:43:59.097 --> 00:44:02.800 align:middle line:84%
They have a lot more techniques
and hardware at their disposal

00:44:02.800 --> 00:44:04.030 align:middle line:90%
to do the analysis.

00:44:04.030 --> 00:44:06.940 align:middle line:84%
But one of the things that
stands clearly in my mind

00:44:06.940 --> 00:44:10.610 align:middle line:84%
is that it was
about 46 years ago

00:44:10.610 --> 00:44:14.440 align:middle line:84%
the last time we sent
a biological detection

00:44:14.440 --> 00:44:15.670 align:middle line:90%
package to Mars.

00:44:15.670 --> 00:44:17.670 align:middle line:84%
And in all that time--
and there was two of them

00:44:17.670 --> 00:44:19.240 align:middle line:90%
on Viking 1 and 2.

00:44:19.240 --> 00:44:21.820 align:middle line:84%
Ever since then, we
have never yet sent

00:44:21.820 --> 00:44:23.720 align:middle line:84%
another biological
detection package.

00:44:23.720 --> 00:44:24.520 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Why not?

00:44:24.520 --> 00:44:27.220 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: So for me,
that says they're not

00:44:27.220 --> 00:44:29.210 align:middle line:90%
looking very seriously.

00:44:29.210 --> 00:44:32.470 align:middle line:84%
And one of the major assumptions
they always seem to make

00:44:32.470 --> 00:44:34.990 align:middle line:84%
is they would only be
looking for microbes.

00:44:34.990 --> 00:44:38.650 align:middle line:84%
And yet, they're dismissing
some pretty glaring examples

00:44:38.650 --> 00:44:41.890 align:middle line:84%
of what appears to be
macro-sized fossils.

00:44:41.890 --> 00:44:42.820 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Fish?

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:47.260 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Well, I haven't seen
any serious evidence of fish.

00:44:47.260 --> 00:44:51.670 align:middle line:84%
But things such as echinoderms,
sea urchins, sand dollars,

00:44:51.670 --> 00:44:52.670 align:middle line:90%
crinoids.

00:44:52.670 --> 00:44:53.470 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Life.

00:44:53.470 --> 00:44:55.137 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Shell--
well, definitely life,

00:44:55.137 --> 00:44:56.680 align:middle line:84%
primitive marine
life, the same sorts

00:44:56.680 --> 00:44:58.430 align:middle line:84%
of things that were
in the oceans of Earth

00:44:58.430 --> 00:44:59.590 align:middle line:90%
200 million years ago.

00:44:59.590 --> 00:45:02.860 align:middle line:84%
But it also extends
the hope that we

00:45:02.860 --> 00:45:05.925 align:middle line:84%
might find some existing
samples deep underground.

00:45:05.925 --> 00:45:07.300 align:middle line:84%
They have found
a number of caves

00:45:07.300 --> 00:45:08.918 align:middle line:84%
and a number of
subsurface lakes.

00:45:08.918 --> 00:45:11.210 align:middle line:84%
And so some of those things
would still be alive today,

00:45:11.210 --> 00:45:13.150 align:middle line:84%
which also brings us
to a cautionary note.

00:45:13.150 --> 00:45:16.090 align:middle line:84%
We know that they're planning
to send human astronauts to Mars

00:45:16.090 --> 00:45:18.130 align:middle line:84%
at some point in the
very near future.

00:45:18.130 --> 00:45:20.170 align:middle line:84%
We have to be cautious
because if there

00:45:20.170 --> 00:45:23.030 align:middle line:84%
are any organisms surviving
on the planet at all,

00:45:23.030 --> 00:45:25.630 align:middle line:84%
it could provide a
real biological threat

00:45:25.630 --> 00:45:27.280 align:middle line:90%
to any people who arrive there.

00:45:27.280 --> 00:45:29.230 align:middle line:84%
We would have
absolutely no resistance

00:45:29.230 --> 00:45:31.185 align:middle line:84%
to any alien
organism, particularly

00:45:31.185 --> 00:45:32.560 align:middle line:84%
if the biochemistry
is different.

00:45:32.560 --> 00:45:33.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And they could
bring it back here.

00:45:33.970 --> 00:45:35.762 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: Well, and
that's the other thing.

00:45:35.762 --> 00:45:37.720 align:middle line:10%
The talk about bringing
samples back I think

00:45:37.720 --> 00:45:39.490 align:middle line:10%
is one of the greatest
foolish things

00:45:39.490 --> 00:45:43.000 align:middle line:10%
we've ever discussed because
it's like putting polio

00:45:43.000 --> 00:45:44.380 align:middle line:10%
blankets in a medical ward.

00:45:44.380 --> 00:45:46.480 align:middle line:84%
You're not going to
get any benefit out

00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:49.600 align:middle line:84%
of this if something
gets out of the lab.

00:45:49.600 --> 00:45:50.980 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Scary times.

00:45:50.980 --> 00:45:52.037 align:middle line:90%
>>SHULTS: It is, indeed.

00:45:52.037 --> 00:45:54.160 align:middle line:84%
So I would say that
the best thing for us

00:45:54.160 --> 00:45:58.870 align:middle line:84%
to do in analyzing this is to
send life-detecting packages

00:45:58.870 --> 00:46:02.055 align:middle line:84%
before we send any human
life there and do not

00:46:02.055 --> 00:46:04.180 align:middle line:84%
bring the samples back
because we really don't have

00:46:04.180 --> 00:46:05.530 align:middle line:90%
secure confinement for them.

00:46:05.530 --> 00:46:07.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Sir Charles, thank you
for being on "Beyond Belief."

00:46:07.870 --> 00:46:09.170 align:middle line:84%
>>SHULTS: It's been a
real pleasure, George.

